        <body>
            <div type="bibliography">
                <p><bibl><ptr target="reycoquais2002"/> <citedRange unit="entry">8</citedRange>, with a plate</bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="SEG"/> <citedRange>52.1608</citedRange></bibl>, <bibl><ptr target="feisselBE"/>2003.580</bibl>, 
                    also <bibl><ptr type="feissel2006"/> <citedRange>683</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="ityr2006"/> <citedRange>134</citedRange></bibl>.
                    </p>
            </div>
            
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
               <ab>
                   <lb n="1"/><g ref="symbol.xml#crux"/> <w lemma="τόπος"><expan><abbr>Τόπ<hi rend="superscript">ο</hi></abbr><ex>ϲ</ex></expan></w>  
                   <orgName ref="#green" nymRef="Πράσινος"><w lemma="παγανός"><expan><abbr>παγ<hi rend="superscript">α</hi></abbr><ex>νῶν</ex></expan></w>
                   <lb n="2"/>    <del rend="erasure"> <supplied reason="lost" cert="low"><w lemma="Πράσινος">Πραϲίνων</w></supplied></del></orgName> 
                   </ab>
             </div> 
           
            <div type="apparatus"><listApp><app loc="2"><rdg resp="#reycoquais2002">παγά(ρχου)</rdg> 
                <rdg resp="#feisselBE">παγα(νῶν)</rdg></app></listApp></div>
           
            <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve">
                <div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" source="#ityr2006"><p>Emplacement du 'pagarque' [des Verts]</p>
           </div>
           <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#cmr"><p>Place of [?Green] pagani?</p>
           </div>
                
         </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Feissel points to the use of paganus for 'ordinary members", citing  <ref target="https://papyri.info/ddbdp/p.oxy;54;3758">P.Oxy 54.3758</ref>, where one group of those liable for payment are called 
                    παγανοί; less clear is what it means in a list by professions <ref target="https://papyri.info/ddbdp/bgu;1;344">BGU 1,344</ref>. Perhaps more relevant is that Paganus 
                    is also used to describe gladiators in at least two funerary texts: 
                    Robert, Gladiateurs 20, at Edessa (available at <ref target="https://epigraphy.packhum.org/text/150969">PHI</ref><!-- check new edition 2015, now no.261, with a bibliography -->) and at Salona, 
                    the funerary urn of a gladiator, <ref target="https://edh.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/edh/inschrift/HD027274">https://edh.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/edh/inschrift/HD027274</ref>.
                    The term is found at Rome in the catalogue of a familia of gladiators (CIL VI, 631, Dessau 5084, whence EDCS 17300774), 
                    under Commodus, where the third decurion lists 2 members as pagani. 
                 
               A couple of funerary inscriptions for pagani with no further explanation, are probably for local ?non-urban people
                https://edh.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/edh/inschrift/HD012630
                https://edh.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/edh/inschrift/HD043121
                Epitaph of Aurelius Hermes paganus - probably a local. 
                 
                </p>
                
            </div>
            
